				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-5664948/scp-3441#post-4428206</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 20 Nov 2019 23:09:25 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Tufto</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3337265</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Wonderfully, subtly dark. It's an interesting skip that explores the implications of a simple premise. The matter-of-fact statements surrounding the interview serve to heighten the central ambiguity of Singh at play. An underrated piece.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-5664948#post-3833378</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-5664948/scp-3441#post-3833378</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 12 Jun 2018 14:01:32 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>sindar_helge</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1395098</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Thank you for alerting me to this! I thought I was through Series 3, but that one must have escaped me.</p> <p>To contribute to the discussion about 3441, I can sort of understand why they put a stop to this. After all, this was reality bending out in the public. Apart from potentially awkward questions (the Foundation has amnestics for these occasions) this is a disturbance of normalcy. In 2822 they can keep the public out of this valley easily enough, and when undisturbed the stone beings leave flesh beings alone. In 3441, the interaction with the public, i.e. the impact on normalcy, is a lot bigger.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
